summary:
This course introduces students to advanced topics in the Python programming language. Students will make use of object-oriented principles to write multi-file programs. Students will make use of modules to quickly build complex software, and will learn to write effective documentation.

This is the second course in the series. It is recommended you complete CNE330 Network Programming in Python before attempting this course.
title: CNE 335 Network Programming in Python II

task_list.name: Functions
task_list.description_text:
Functions

In Python, a function is a named sequence of statements that belong together. Their primary purpose is to help us organize programs into chunks that match how we think about the solution to the problem.

The syntax for a function definition is:


    def name( parameters ):
        statements

It is common to use placeholder functions in testing, that behave like the actual function without hardware. These often prefixed with fake, mock, or dummy, such as fake_ping

Problem

1. Write a fake_ping function, that takes a server_ip and a ping_time, and returns a string

2. Have the ping function call fake_ping with a ping time of 10ms, and return the result of the fake_ping function. Have the fake_ping function return a string that says "Ping response from [server_ip] [ping_time]"

As an example, if you wrote ping("127.0.0.1"), the code should return:

"Ping response from 127.0.0.1 10ms"

server_ip and ping_time are strings.

Both functions, ping and fake_ping, should return a string (str). This means you don't need to use print in your code, though it is fine for testing and debugging.

task_list.name: Selection
task_list.description_text:
Conditional Statements

In order to write useful programs, we almost always need the ability to check conditions and change the behavior of the program accordingly. Selection statements, sometimes also referred to as conditional statements, give us this ability. The simplest form of selection is the if statement. This is sometimes referred to as binary selection since there are two possible paths of execution.

The syntax for an if statement looks like this:


    if BOOLEAN EXPRESSION:
        STATEMENTS_1        # executed if condition evaluates to True
    else:
        STATEMENTS_2        # executed if condition evaluates to False

Problem

1. Write a is_ip_localhost function, that takes a server_ip and checks if it is equal to 127.0.0.1. If yes, return True. If no, return False.

As an example, if you wrote is_local_or_remote("127.0.0.1"), the code should return a boolean:

True

2. Write a who_assigned_ip function, that takes a server_ip and returns:

Localhost if ip is 127.0.0.1

DHCP if the ip starts with 192.168.0

Unknown otherwise

server_ip is a string.

True should be a bool, not a string.

task_list.name: Lists
task_list.description_text:
Lists

A list is a sequential collection of Python data values, where each value is identified by an index. The values that make up a list are called its elements. Lists are similar to strings, which are ordered collections of characters, except that the elements of a list can have any type and for any one list, the items can be of different types.

A list within another list is said to be nested and the inner list is often called a sublist. Finally, there is a special list that contains no elements. It is called the empty list and is denoted [].

Problem

1. Write a fake_create_initial_network_list function, that creates a list with 3 IP addresses. IPs are your choice, 127.0.0.1, etc.

2. Write a fake_add_to_network function, that takes a network list and an ip, and adds the new IP to the list.

3. Write a get_server_at_index function, that takes a network list and an index into the list, and return the IP. Return "None" if an invalid (such as -10) or out-of-range index is provided.

task_list.name: Dictionaries
task_list.description_text:
Dictionaries

Dictionaries are a different kind of collection. They are Pythonâ€™s built-in mapping type. A map is an unordered, associative collection. The association, or mapping, is from a key, which can be any immutable type, to a value, which can be any Python data object.

One way to create a dictionary is to start with the empty dictionary and add key-value pairs. The empty dictionary is denoted {}

Problem

A Domain Name Server converts site names, like google.com, to their IP address 172.217.3.174. Using a dictionary is faster than a list, because you do not need to check other elements to find the right one.

1. Write a fake_create_initial_network_dict function, that creates a dict with three items, make the server name be the key (i.e. google.com), and the server ip be the value (i.e. 172.217.3.174)

2. Write a fake_add_to_network function, that takes a network dictionary, a server name, and an ip, and adds the new IP to the list.

3. Write a fake_dns_lookup function, that takes a network dict and a server name, and returns the IP. Return "Not found" if name doesn't exist.

task_list.name: For Loops
task_list.description_text:
For loops

The for loop processes each item in a list. Each item in turn is (re-)assigned to the loop variable, and the body of the loop is executed.

Problem

A Domain Name Server converts site names, like google.com, to their IP address 172.217.3.174. Using a dictionary is faster than a list, because you do not need to check other elements to find the right one.

1. Write a fake_create_initial_network_list function, that creates list dict with 1000 random IPs.

2. Write a ip_in_network_list function, that takes a network list and an IP, and returns the IP if it was found in the last. Return "Not found" if name doesn't exist.

task_list.name: While Loops
task_list.description_text:
While Loops

There is another Python statement that can also be used to build an iteration. It is called the while statement. The while statement provides a much more general mechanism for iterating. Similar to the if statement, it uses a boolean expression to control the flow of execution. The body of while will be repeated as long as the controlling boolean expression evaluates to True.

Problem

Write a function, get_log_event_list that takes 2 strings, a file_name and an event, and uses a while loop to output a list containing the lines where the event was found:

1. Create an empty list to hold the matching lines

2. Open a the file for reading

3. Use a while loop to check if the file has a next line, or if the next line is blank

4. In the while loop, if the event string is found in the line, add it to the list.

5. In the while loop, read the next line.

6. Outside the while loop, return the list.

Use readline()

task_list.name: 17_4 User-Defined Classes
task_list.description_text:
17.4 User-Defined Classes

An object combines variables and functions into a single entity. Objects get their variables and functions from classes. Classes are essentially templates for creating your objects. You can think of an object as a single data structure that contains data as well as functions. Functions of objects are called methods.

Problem

Create a variable, server_name, and assign a value to it inside `ServerClass`.

task_list.name: 17_5 Improving our Constructor
task_list.description_text:
17.5 Improving our Constructor

A function that creates a new object instance is called a constructor. Every class automatically uses the name of the class as the name of the constructor function. The definition of the constructor function is done when you write the __init__ function.

It may be helpful to think of a class as a factory for making objects. The class itself isnâ€™t an instance of a point, but it contains the machinery to make point instances. Every time you call the constructor, youâ€™re asking the factory to make you a new object. As the object comes off the production line, its initialization method is executed to get the object properly set up with its factory default settings.

The combined process of â€œmake me a new objectâ€ and â€œget its settings initialized to the factory default settingsâ€ is called instantiation.

Problem

Add a server_name variable to the __init__ function

task_list.name: 17_6 Adding Other Methods
task_list.description_text:
17.6 Adding Other Methods

A method behaves like a function, but it is invoked on a specific instance. For example, with a server named linux, linux.set_server_ip('192.168.0.1') asks the server object to perform its set_server_ip method, and set the server_ip to 192.168.0.1. Methods are accessed using dot notation.

All methods defined in a class that operate on objects of that class will have self as their first parameter. This serves as reference to the object itself which in turn gives access to the state data inside the object.

Problem

Add a method, get_server_ip, that returns the object's server_ip.

task_list.name: 17_7 Objects as Arguments
task_list.description_text:
17.7 Objects as Arguments

You can pass an object as an argument in the usual way.

Problem

Create a function, biggest_ip_sum, outside of the ServerClass class, that:

1. Takes two ServerClass objects

2. Sums the octets of the IP together (example 127.0.0.1 = 127+0+0+1 = 128)

3. Returns the larger number

Example:

server_one = ServerClass("127.0.0.1")

server_two = ServerClass("192.168.0.1")

result = biggest_ip_sum(server_one, server_two)

print(result)

In the example above, result will be 361.

task_list.name: 17_9 Instances as Return Values
task_list.description_text:
17.9 Instances as Return Values

Functions and methods can return objects. This is actually nothing new since everything in Python is an object and we have been returning values for quite some time. The difference here is that we want to have the method create an object using the constructor and then return it as the value of the method.

Problem

Create two server objects using the class

create a function, biggest_server_object_sum, outside of the ServerClass class, that:

1. Takes an IP

2. Sums the octets of the IP together (example 127.0.0.1 = 127+0+0+1 = 128)

3. Returns the Server object with the larger sum

Example:

server_one = ServerClass("127.0.0.1")

server_two = ServerClass("192.168.0.1")

result = biggest_ip_sum(server_one, server_two)

print(result)

Modify get_server_ip in the previous problem.

task_list.name: 18_0 Classes Review
task_list.description_text:
18.0 Review: User Defined Classes (17.4), Adding other Methods (17.6)

Every class should have a method with the special name __init__. This initializer method, often referred to as the constructor, is automatically called whenever a new instance of the object is created. It gives the programmer the opportunity to set up the attributes required within the new instance by giving them their initial state values. The self parameter (you could choose any other name, but nobody ever does!) is automatically set to reference the newly-created object that needs to be initialized.

The key advantage of using a class rather than something like a simple tuple is methods. We can add methods to any class that are sensible operations. Creating a class brings an exceptional amount of â€œorganizational powerâ€ to our programs, and to our thinking. We can group together the sensible operations, and the kinds of data they apply to, and each instance of the class can have its own state.

A method behaves like a function, but it is invoked on a specific instance. For example, with a turtle named tess, tess.right(90) asks the tess object to perform its right method and turn 90 degrees. Methods are accessed using dot notation.

Problem

No starter code is provided. Your tasks:

1. Create a class, BareMetalServer

2. Inside the class, write a constructor that takes CPU, GPU, RAM, and HDD variables and stores them

3. Add a method, get_system_info, that returns the system info in an array. Example: [CPU, GPU, RAM, HDD]

task_list.name: 18_0 Classes Review II
task_list.description_text:
18.0 Review II: Objects as Arguments and Parameters (17.7), Instances as Return Values (17.9)

You can pass an object as an argument in the usual way. Functions and methods can return objects. This is actually nothing new since everything in Python is an object and we have been returning values for quite some time. The difference here is that we want to have the method create an object using the constructor and then return it as the value of the method.

Problem

You will create two classes, NetworkCardClass and NetworkServerClass.

In NetworkCardClass:

1. Add constructor that stores an ip_address (str) and a model_name (str)

In NetworkServerClass:

1. Add constructor that stores an ip_address (str) and a network_card (NetworkCardClass)

2. Add a method, get_server_details, that returns the system info as a string. Example: "Name: AWS EC2 IP: 36.63.23.21 Network Card: Intel Gigabit Adapter"

task_list.name: 18_2 Objects are Mutable
task_list.description_text:
18.2 Objects are Mutable

We can change the state of an object by making an assignment to one of its instance variables. For example, we could change the ip by assigning a new value to self.ip.

We could also have an external function modify self.ip. This type of function is often called a helper function. Second, the request_dhcp_ip method does not return anything. Its job is to modify the object itself. This type of method is known as a mutator method because it mutates or changes the internal state of the object.

Problem

We want to create a DHCP service that assigns a random, unique IP with subnet mask 255.0.0.0. This means the service only sets the last 3 octets of an IP. For example if the dhcp_service function is called by an IP of "192.0.0.0", it should keep the 192 and change the rest:

1. Create a dhcp_service(ip_address) function, outside of the ServerClass

2. Have request_dhcp_ip call dhcp_service and set the ServerClass object's IP to the generated IP

task_list.name: 19_2 Introduction to Inheritance I
task_list.description_text:
19.2 Introduction to Inheritance

Suppose we want to create a class that works like ServerClass in every respect, but also keeps track of the Operating System. We could create a ServerWithOperatingSystem class by copying and pasting the definition for ServerClass, changing the name to ServerWithOperatingSystem, and modifying the class to suit our purposes. However, any time you copy and paste code, keep in mind that you are copying and pasting bugs that may exist in the code. Inheritance provides a way to reuse the definition of ServerClass without having to copy and paste.

Problem

In task.py:

1. Create a ServerWithOperatingSystemClass object. Have ServerWithOperatingSystemClass inherit from ServerClass.

2. Add a constructor (hint: __init__) to ServerWithOperatingSystemClass that stores ip, name, and operating_system variables.

3. Add a get_inherited_server_class_information method to ServerWithOperatingSystemClass. It should call get_server_class_information in ServerClass and append OS information. Example: "Name: AzureVM IP: 36.63.12.45 OS: Windows"

task_list.name: 19_2 Introduction to Inheritance II
task_list.description_text:
19.2 Introduction to Inheritance

Now, suppose we want to create a class that works like ServerClass in every respect, but also keeps track of the AWS instance type. We could create a AWSServer class by copying and pasting the definition for ServerClass, changing the name to AWSServer, and modifying the class to suit our purposes. However, any time you copy and paste code, keep in mind that you are copying and pasting bugs that may exist in the code. Inheritance provides a way to reuse the definition of ServerClass without having to copy and paste.

Problem

Create a ServerClass object, have AWSServer inherit from ServerClass, and then create a ServerClass object and an AWSServer object in task.py:

In ServerClass.py:

1. Create an __init__ with ip and name variables

In AWSServer.py:

1. Create a class that inherits from ServerClass

2. Create an __init__ with ip, name, and instance_type variables

In task.py:

1. Import ServerClass object from ServerClass.py

2. Import AWSServer object from AWSServer.py

3. Create a local_server variable of ServerClass type. Initialize the variables to your choice.

4. Create an aws_server variable of AWSServer type. Initialize the variables to your choice.

task_list.name: 19_5 Class Diagrams
task_list.description_text:
19.5 Class Diagrams

When two classes are involved in an inheritance or composition relationship, we say that an association exists between them. Often it is helpful to depict the associations between classes on a graphical diagram, so that developers working on the code can see at a glance how the classes are related to each other. The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a graphical notation that provides a standard for depicting classes and their associations on various types of diagrams. Class diagrams can contain a number of different elements, but we will focus on the basics: depicting classes with their instance variables and methods, and relationships to other classes.

On a UML class diagram, a class is depicted as a rectangle with three sections. The top section contains the class name; the middle section, the instance variables; and the bottom section, the methods.

Problem

In this final problem, you will design an access control system, similar to what you see in an operating system.

Implement the classes based on this UML diagram, and write the add_action in the User class.

Starting with the base code in the User class, code the Admin, NormalUser, and PowerUser classes. They will inherit from the User class.

Next, write the add_action method in User. add_action should check if the call was made by an Admin.

The NormalUser, PowerUser, and Admin constructors (hint: __init__) are almost the same as the User class. You could copy-and-paste much of the User constructor into those Py files to get some tests passing.

add_action should only work for Admins. One way to do this is to check if the user who called add_action (self) has "Admin" in their type string. For example if str(type(self)) == "Admin":
